    thinking: "**Designing Client-Side State**\n\nI\'m making excellent progress on the client-side state hooks. I\'m focusing on creating them in `/src/App.tsx` or a custom store file. The custom hook approach seems like a tidy solution, and I\'m particularly interested in managing the current active page view (\'home\' | \'menu\' | etc.) with it.\n\n\n**Refining State Structure**\n\nI\'ve decided to refine the state structure. I\'m leaning toward keeping the state within `/src/App.tsx`, or potentially in `/src/context/AppContext.tsx`. The current plan is to pass it down as props for transparency and performance. I\'m focusing on the different components of the state, including the active page view, the cart item list, active reservations, and a simulated checkout sequence for order confirmation. Also, the page components such as the `Navbar` and `Hero` section will live under the `/src/components/` directory. I\'m considering structuring it as a custom React context to streamline state management.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will create the `/src/components/Navbar.tsx` component. It features a sticky navigation layout with custom fonts, elegant styling, fluid page transition routing markers, and a real-time responsive shopping cart badge that triggers the Cart overlay. All colors fit the rust/cocoa/dark espresso cafe guidelines."
